# iOS Face ID in Capacitor: a complete implementation guide for NDA signing

The "Confirm with Side Button" double-press flow **cannot be triggered by third-party apps** — it is an Apple-exclusive hardware interaction reserved for Apple Pay and App Store purchases, wired directly to the Secure Enclave at the firmware level. Third-party apps instead use `LAContext` from the LocalAuthentication framework, which produces a simpler dialog-based Face ID prompt. For your Capacitor-based NDA signing app, the strongest achievable approach combines a Capacitor biometric plugin (triggering `LAContext` under the hood), a **biometric-gated Secure Enclave signing key** that creates cryptographic proof of authentication, and **Apple's App Attest API** for device integrity — all relayed through Firebase with challenge-response anti-replay protections.

---

## The double-press side button is hardware-locked to Apple's payment flows

The animated "Double Click to [Install/Pay]" prompt seen in App Store purchases and Apple Pay is not produced by any public API available to third-party developers. It is a **system-level interaction** tied to PassKit (`PKPaymentAuthorizationController`) and StoreKit, where the physical double-click of the side button is wired at the hardware/firmware layer directly to the Secure Enclave. Apple introduced this gesture specifically because Face ID works passively — unlike Touch ID, where placing a finger served as both intent and biometric, Face ID needed a separate physical intent signal to prevent accidental purchases.

When a third-party app calls `LAContext.evaluatePolicy(.deviceOwnerAuthenticationWithBiometrics, localizedReason:)`, the resulting UX is fundamentally different. Face ID activates **silently and automatically** — the TrueDepth camera scans without showing any dialog on the first attempt. If the scan succeeds, the callback fires immediately with no visible UI at all. Only on failure does a centered dialog appear with a Face ID icon and "Try Again" button. This contrasts sharply with the full-screen payment sheet shown by Apple Pay. There is no public API, private API, or entitlement that allows a third-party app to show the double-click animation or full payment sheet experience.

The closest alternative for making biometric auth feel deliberate is a **two-step confirmation pattern**: display a custom in-app confirmation screen ("You are about to sign this NDA. Tap 'Confirm & Verify' to proceed"), then trigger `LAContext` only after the user explicitly taps. This mimics the intent-then-authenticate pattern of Apple Pay without requiring the hardware double-click. Combined with a biometric-gated Secure Enclave key (detailed below), this creates a architecturally strong signing flow.

