## Cross-device QR relay stays the same, with critical security additions

Using native iOS biometric auth via Capacitor **replaces only the client-side biometric prompt** on Party B's device. The Firebase relay pattern remains identical — the change is what gets sent as the verification payload.

The core security problem: after `NativeBiometric.verifyIdentity()` resolves, the JavaScript layer constructs a "I verified successfully" message to send through Firebase. **This self-reported boolean is trivially forgeable on jailbroken devices.** The Capacitor plugin documentation explicitly warns that `verifyIdentity()` should not be the sole authentication mechanism. The cryptographic layers above are what make the result trustworthy.

### Secure relay payload schema

```json
{
  "verification_sessions": {
    "<sessionId>": {
      "request": {
        "creatorUid": "party-a-firebase-uid",
        "nonce": "crypto-random-32-byte-hex",
        "documentHash": "sha256-of-nda-content",
        "createdAt": { ".sv": "timestamp" },
        "expiresAt": 1711723200000
      },
      "result": {
        "signerUid": "party-b-firebase-uid",
        "nonce": "echoed-nonce-from-request",
        "documentHash": "echoed-sha256-of-nda",
        "signature": "base64-ecdsa-from-secure-enclave",
        "publicKey": "base64-der-public-key",
        "attestationToken": "firebase-app-check-token",
        "biometryType": "faceID",
        "timestamp": { ".sv": "timestamp" }
      },
      "validated": {
        "verifiedAt": { ".sv": "timestamp" },
        "signatureValid": true,
        "appCheckConsumed": true
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Never transmit** raw biometric data (iOS prevents this by design), private keys, the bare boolean result of `verifyIdentity()`, or full NDA content (only the hash). **Firebase Realtime Database** is preferred over Firestore for this relay pattern due to lower latency (~600ms roundtrip vs ~1500ms).

### Firebase security rules enforce one-time write and session binding

```json
{
  "rules": {
    "verification_sessions": {
      "$sessionId": {
        ".read": "auth != null && (data.child('request/creatorUid').val() === auth.uid || data.child('result/signerUid').val() === auth.uid)",
        "request": {
          ".write": "auth != null && !data.exists()",
          ".validate": "newData.hasChildren(['creatorUid','nonce','documentHash','createdAt','expiresAt']) && newData.child('creatorUid').val() === auth.uid && newData.child('expiresAt').val() > now && newData.child('expiresAt').val() <= (now + 600000)"
        },
        "result": {
          ".write": "auth != null && !data.exists() && root.child('verification_sessions').child($sessionId).child('request').exists() && root.child('verification_sessions').child($sessionId).child('request/expiresAt').val() > now && root.child('verification_sessions').child($sessionId).child('request/creatorUid').val() !== auth.uid",
          ".validate": "newData.child('nonce').val() === root.child('verification_sessions').child($sessionId).child('request/nonce').val() && newData.child('documentHash').val() === root.child('verification_sessions').child($sessionId).child('request/documentHash').val()"
        },
        "validated": { ".write": false }
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Key protections: `!data.exists()` prevents replay by ensuring one-time write; nonce and document hash must match between request and result; `expiresAt` caps sessions at 10 minutes; `creatorUid !== auth.uid` prevents self-verification; the `validated` node is write-locked to clients — only Cloud Functions using Admin SDK can write it.

### Cloud Functions as the trusted validator

A callable Cloud Function with `enforceAppCheck: true` and `consumeAppCheckToken: true` serves as the authoritative verification layer. It verifies the ECDSA signature against Party B's registered public key, checks the App Check token (consuming it to prevent reuse), validates nonce freshness and document hash match, and writes the authoritative `validated` node via Admin SDK.

