## Conclusion

The implementation path for your NDA signing app has three layers of increasing strength. The **minimum viable approach** uses a Capacitor biometric plugin (`@capgo/capacitor-native-biometric` or `@aparajita/capacitor-biometric-auth`) to trigger Face ID, providing a good user experience but no cryptographic proof. The **recommended approach** adds a Secure Enclave P-256 signing key protected by `.biometryCurrentSet`, where signing the NDA hash inherently requires Face ID and produces verifiable ECDSA evidence. The **full defense-in-depth approach** layers in App Attest (via Firebase App Check) for device integrity, server-side signature verification via Cloud Functions, and an immutable audit trail with RFC 3161 timestamps. The Secure Enclave key path requires native Swift code exposed as a custom Capacitor plugin, since the existing biometric plugins abstract away `LAContext` and do not expose Keychain or Secure Enclave operations — but this native bridge is a one-time engineering investment that transforms your biometric verification from a forgeable boolean into cryptographic proof.